The feeding of an obese child: does not take breakfast and takes charcuterie for dinner
More than a third of 9 to 13-year-olds have problems with overweight, 9% of schoolchildren are overweight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families who have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This shows again how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the patterns around him.
On the tables of obese children, for example, charcuterie is found 50% more often than in families of normal weight children.
19% of obese people had chips at dinner, according to the survey conducted with an awareness-raising action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In the families of small adults, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren today - only 15% answered that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
A survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
It was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", supported by General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 sixth to third grade students have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough exercise.
“For example, only half of the children surveyed reported eating breakfast five times a day — lunch — snack — dinner, which is one of the basic principles of a good diet,” one of the survey results said.
Without breakfast and charcuterie at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development you need some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students’ families eat at the same time.
In most of the families, everyone has their own breakfast.
And the worst thing that has been found is that one tenth of the population does not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast, however, is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in the families of obese children, unhealthy chips are consumed more often.
Almost every student – not to mention their weight – drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of children surveyed do sports regularly, but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare Your Diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diet from possibilities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
“The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal, in terms of healthy eating.”
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is particularly a great preference for sweet lemonades," the results of the survey said.
For lunch it is the pasta that took the first place just in front of the white meat.
The children did not want any starch at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Heading on Health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
“During a survey of a group of survey participants who filled out the questionnaire after the ‘Obesity is not a coincidence’ awareness session, a determined desire to move towards a healthy diet was felt,” the survey results said.
The most notable was, for example, for sweet lemonades as children began to give preference to drinking water.
The children most often checked white meat and fish as the main dish on the questionnaire and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread flour balls or potatoes).
