IBM's History: From Cheese slices to Spaceflights.
The IBM (International Business Machines) company was born in New York a hundred years ago; it originally had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It was renamed IBM in 1924 – it was originally a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is related to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They possessed technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 chaired the company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then made the shadow to the founder of the firm - it is on Watson's ideas that so far rest the identity and culture of the company.
Watson led the firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce – from cheese and meat slicers to checkout boxes.
During the first four years of Watson’s leadership, revenue grew to $9 million and the company began to expand to all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of management, it was his son who occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM's people and computers helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers – the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 came to market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer factory to Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with consulting and services with high value added.
The strategy that IBM has succeeded in the last three years is the Smarter Planet concept “a smarter planet.”
Its objective is to intelligently harness technology in areas that are not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
As far as commerce is concerned, IBM recently developed a “Smart Commerce” platform that helps traders manage the entire business cycle.
