How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter otherwise individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, however, it was necessary to queue up all night with a sleeping bag or have "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The agreement for currencies that was the condition for traveling to the west was refused to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The travels of the Czechs have been undergoing a major revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at the maximum,the Czechs spent 4 million days abroad in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in neighbouring countries of the West has caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for long travel by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel agencies had Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip at that time was to bring with him his own canned food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which finally allowed our tourists after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as average wages have increased, leading to another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the growing demand for travel, travel agencies have started to prepare tours since 1997 with air charters that, thanks to contracts, have dramatically reduced costs compared to before.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most of the developed countries around the world except the US, which later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year, direct air charters take Czech tourists to the distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development happened in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully rank in the group of developed countries.
In 2008, for the first time in history, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history again spent more than 15,000 kroner per person for a holiday abroad including appendices.
