Peter Englund's new book, "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War," begins with a long list of characters that draw your heart.
A tip to get started: carefully tear this page and make it your page marker.
In this romantic tale of Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a tag during these few moments where, as one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the fog of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which delivers the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book which he accurately describes as "a work of anti-history."
It contains some known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is hardly any ambassador or discussion of strategies and material.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like," where you find the "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and sorrow" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, to doctors, ambulances and salesmen.
Some of them will become heroes.
Some of the prisoners of war will lose their members, become mad, or lose their lives.
Their lives swirl here like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are lit up.
Peter Englund's book differs from traditional history books.
It denies the idea that the First World War is summarized only by the terrible trenches war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skillfully describes other war theaters: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one Christmas pass in Egypt under the pyramids; the tsé-tsé flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that blows the whirlwind.
When gunshots resound in the distance, and you’re a mother at home, do you stay or run away?
Who's gonna come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been exaggerated by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
