How to Find a Lie
A look at recent headlines shows how omnipresent deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was picked up by an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed careers and shaken countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, has passed for an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the coverage of an extramarital relationship.
And then, none of those who have lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating on the tests of the school and the university are legion.
There have been instances where teachers gave test responses to students in order to be clearly seen on their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach otherwise send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game of society similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to write: "I had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected during the last six decades, especially in phylogenetic research projects in prestigious universities.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lies have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don’t blush, blush, or bother all the time.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to uncover.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, question formation and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating in our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include, in particular, hiring.
Good liars are capable of reading others well, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extraverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more lies "focused on themselves" while women tell more lies "focused on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people have to be "normal" than married people lie to their partners less often than married people.
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is what is called "establishing benchmark data".
This helps to provide a point of reference for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, laughter, vocal quality.
You need to know if someone normally moves their feet constantly so as not to make unfair accusations when you see them move their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and non-verbal deceptive behavior.
Consider these indices as red flags, not proof of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the upper body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet towards the door, lean toward an exit, change post-interview significantly, or present a relief from "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all questions are not difficult.
Questionnaires often falsely indicate that the interview is finished just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to your subject’s vocabulary.
Famous Scott Peterson has erased using the past while claiming his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use remote language: “I haven’t had sex with this woman...Ms. Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
One can use a lot of "wooden tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember goods... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
