First of all, I don’t think any of us had imagined we were going to form a big rock band, and the fact that we’ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together makes us very emotional.
We love each other and we love to create music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world we have always wanted to go.
Things couldn't get better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in creating grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group of big groups.
We are very friendly with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honor for us to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
“Last year we participated in a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to still be friends with all of them and it’s an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that emerged.
It is also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that is much longer than many bands normally last.
Firstly, I believe we are all lucky to be alive, and secondly, we all care about others.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t get any better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don’t spend too much time on tour because it’s easy to fall into this game of great crowds and people who love your music.
If we don’t forget that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we have to respect music and what brought it, without thinking about the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which doesn’t really interest any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some good songs and at first it was great.
We’ve been a band for almost three years and we didn’t release a record before Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration for the fact that it lasted so little and the most important thing is the fact that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the group with us and when I listen to a song or I see a lot of other stuff that I've been laughing at and I've been laughing at the amazing person that Andy's been faisa to me.
He was a surprising human being and we miss him.
The national group Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know his work, especially Eddie Vedder and that's why you chose him for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with different proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we’re looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and it must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words of Yello Ledbetter live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don’t know.
It is he who sings it and I believe he does it with the first words he imagines.
As a bassist, what are his influences?
There are so many...
Among the first ones I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge under control despite the fact that it is no longer fashionable?
I think we all feel a bit disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came up at the same time and, if that's relevant now, I think it's wonderful because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney now make the best music.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
That’s interesting, because I think there are songs in the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe, that qualify as very dark songs, although these may sound a bit positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deeply obscure songs.
I think if you grow up and there’s a trauma in your life and you lose a parent or friend, these things start to influence your art and your music and these songs probably represent that to me.
I also think you can be happy and even like that you can make dark music.
