During the press conference, the holder of the SCT, Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Full Visual:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, which means that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
<0xE2><0x80><0xA2> Weather conditions:
Reports in the ICMA mentioned adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft progressed towards the adjacent area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-altitude clouds.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew sought a lower altitude area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the aircraft's last radar recording coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a reduced area:
The information available so far makes it possible to assume that the impact took place on a straight and lateral path.
The model of dispersion of the aircraft remains makes it possible to assume that the helicopter has hit the ground in conditions of structural integrity.
