Thus was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Cali dactyloscopist has gone down in history as the man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cano.
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4, a CTI typist from Cali went down in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the Supreme Chief of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano", confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists working in the local offices of the ICC, this week was the turn of the “availability” of Elias Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the field of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez worked in the municipalities of Choc<0xC3><0xB3>, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to arrive at the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he moved to the capital of Valle and after taking appropriate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of the friction skin, i.e. the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliasar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who ran the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo Le<0xC3><0xB3>n S<0xC3><0xA1>enz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the place of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much leaner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a pickup and a lantern, Eliasar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the responsible who confirmed to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinz<0xC3><0xB3>n that yes, he was the Supreme Chief of the FARC.
In Search of the Imprint
For a Sij<0xC3><0xAD>n de Cali dactyloscopist, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliasar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without margin of error, that can be crucial in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, fingerprinters support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false ID cards or do not have any documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher reported that in a case of theft he had to remove a part of the wall of a house, because in that place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
“The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to draw a fingerprint from them, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint of the entire hand and identify the offender who had participated in different thefts,” he recalls.
Footprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently, a dead man was found, with bottles of drink around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a parent may be a suspect of the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he is the murderer, it places him on the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprinter explained that "the fingerprints of objects with chemical or physical reagents are extracted."
When they appear, a picker or strip is used to pick them up.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the declining database, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of Colombians without papers," said the ITC expert.
He explained that not everything is how it is shown in the CSI television program.
As everything that shines is not gold, everything that one touches does not necessarily become a footprint.
It can be used, however, if the necessary confrontation is realized.
