Restricting immigration anemies growth and harms employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants are likely to replace national workers, especially the low-skilled, putting down pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, exercising most of the professions in sectors with a shortage of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the job offer.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have a hard time working in a country with a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
