The Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia through the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part on Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first tube of 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline must be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas to be delivered, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same path.
For Gazprom, the timely and timely completion of this huge construction site has the air of victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream will in fact make it possible to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland, in 1939.
That is, whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by providing its support to this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has triumphed its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, heavily gas-consuming, and whose deposits are declining.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that ties us organically,” Fillon said in his inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic gas contracts are.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-coiled steel to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
To build it, minefields dating back to the Second World War had to be avoided.
"One hundred had to be kidnapped or destroyed, by precaution," said Jens Müller, a spokesperson for Nord Stream.
Measures to protect the flora and fauna also had to be multiplied.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve, nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project leaders gave up while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company permanently established off their coasts.
“In case of failure, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
But this case is deemed unlikely by manufacturers who have planned welding to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced into the tube, wide by one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it delivers accurate information about possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to run for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty years renewable, the entire gas transport capacity.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided at 30% by shareholders and at 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to come back at their own expense, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour passing.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
